data.title: Surf Life Saving NSW
data.text:
#SURFSPORTS // The Lifesaving World Championships have begun on the Gold Coast this week, with National teams ready to represent their countries from tomorrow.

Sunday saw the Australian Open and Youth teams presented with their Green & Gold caps in front of family members. We are so proud of the four NSW athletes representing in the Australian Youth team:

🟢 Brayden Woodford - Bulli Surf Life Saving Club

🟡 Mischa Boniface - Mollymook Surf Life Saving Club Inc.

🟢 Lani Waller - Redhead SLSC

🟡 Kobe Sorensen – North Cronulla Surf Life Saving Club

Good luck and we are sure you will do your clubs, your state, and your country proud!

#AOE24 // A huge season with a record number of rescues has been celebrated and reflected on by nearly 500 volunteer lifesavers and their supporters, coming together on Saturday 24 August for the annual Surf Life Saving NSW Awards of Excellence event in Sydney.

Read our full wrap of the night and see full list of winners 👉 bit.ly/4dUdW88

#AOE24 // The NSW Awards of Excellence is over for another year ✨

What an amazing night celebrating the excellence within Surf Life Saving in NSW. Congratulations to all our winners, you deserve all the recognition.

To all our finalists, we are so proud of you and all you achieved.

Thank you for joining us for a night of celebration. See you next year!

#AOE24 // Congratulations to Mollie Murphy from Umina Surf Life Saving Club, our 2024 Surf Lifesaver of the Year ✨

This is her second major award in just a couple of weeks after being named the Rotary Emergency Services Community Awards winner in early August.

Mollie is the Director of Lifesaving at Umina SLSC and continues a proud tradition of incredible young volunteer lifesavers to come from the region. She completed nearly 150 hours of patrols this past season and is active in promoting youth within her club and the Branch as well.

Her efforts, influenced by her involvement in the SLSA National Leadership College and Women’s Mentoring Program, led to a significant rise in youth participation, lifesaving qualifications, and overall club pride. Her dedication has particularly empowered young females, driving a notable increase in their achievements within the club.

Thank you for everything you do Mollie.

#AOE24 // // Congratulations to Elyse McMaster from Evans Head-Casino SLSC, this year's Volunteer of the Year ✨

Elyse is a selfless and dedicated volunteer surf life saver, parent, leader, and mentor of Evans Head-Casino SLSC. With over 20 years in the movement, she is highly committed to providing youth members opportunities to engage with their community.

As the current Junior Activities Coordinator at her Club, Elyse is working to provide a new approach towards youth development, and support Age Managers so they can ensure appropriate levels of learning is applied within the Nippers program.

She is one of only 3 female IRB drivers in Evans Head-Casino SLSC and has also been a key part of the Club’s annual Pink Patrol. She describes her club as feeling “like home” and she’s our 2024 Volunteer of the year!

#AOE24 // Congratulations to the 2024 Athlete of the year, for the second year in a row, Daniel Collins from Redhead SLSC ✨

Dan had another outstanding year in Surf Sports with the highlight of the season being his incredible win in the Open Ironman race at Aussies. In doing so, he became the first man from the Hunter and the fourth from a NSW club to win the Aussies title.

This was an incredibly exciting race with the conditions being very tricky - sideway winds, driving rain and messy surf. Dan entered the water for the last leg in 5th or 6th, but his swim leg is his strongest and it did not disappoint; he powered through the field to come out the convincing winner.

Dan maintains a busy schedule as a patrolling member and full-time lifeguard, but he still always finds time to give back to the movement.

#AOE24 // Huge congratulations to Terrigal Surf Life Saving Club, winners of the 2024 Club of the Year ✨

Terrigal has maintained a 274 strong and highly skilled cohort of patrolling members, serving a beach with large tourist numbers. They performed 22 rescues this season but this number could have been significantly greater as they were able to mitigate over 2,000 situations that may have escalated due to their vigilance on the beach.

The club has actively engaged the wider community through a host of key events not only for locals but for the region as a whole, and has leant on strong, distinguished leadership through its Board of Management to secure critical facilities upgrades and mentoring future leaders of the club.

Well done Terrigal SLSC!

#AOE24 // Congratulations to Hunter Surf Lifesaving winners of the 2024 Branch of the Year ✨

Hunter Branch has worked hard throughout 2023-24 to engage with their broader community and take proactive steps to build stronger communities across the region. They saw a spike of 800 members during the season, while members were particularly active on the beach recording increases in rescues, patrol hours, first aids and preventative actions.

The Branch has shown a deep investment in the future of lifesaving by nurturing its younger members, specifically those aged 15-18. The Branch successfully secured grants exceeding $10,000, which were used to acquire advanced training equipment and drones. These tools not only offer practical learning experiences but also keep young members engaged.

Congratulations to Hunter Branch on being named the 2024 Branch of the Year!
